  "prompt": "Why can't radio waves transmit through water?",
  "response": "Actually, radio waves can transmit through water, but with significant limitations. The effectiveness depends on several factors:\n\n1. Frequency: Low-frequency radio waves can penetrate water to some degree, while high-frequency waves are quickly absorbed.\n\n2. Depth: The depth of water greatly affects radio wave transmission. As depth increases, signal strength rapidly decreases.\n\n3. Water conductivity: Saltwater is more conductive and absorbs radio waves more quickly than freshwater.\n\n4. Signal attenuation: Water molecules absorb and scatter radio waves, causing signal degradation.\n\nThis is why underwater communication typically uses very low frequency (VLF) or extremely low frequency (ELF) waves for submarine communication, or alternative methods like acoustic waves.\n\nSome specific points about radio wave transmission in water:\n- AM radio waves can penetrate water slightly better than FM waves\n- At greater depths, signal strength drops exponentially\n- Submarines use extremely low-frequency radio waves for limited communication\n- For most practical underwater communication, alternative methods like sonar are more effective\n\nSo it's not entirely accurate to say radio waves can't transmit through water - they can, but with significant limitations.",
